    LastInSorted<TItem>(IEnumerable<TItem>, Func<TItem, Boolean>)

    A non-cached version of System.Linq.Enumerable.Last``1(System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable{``0},System.Func{``0,System.Boolean}) for sorted collections.

    Declaration
    public static TItem LastInSorted<TItem>(this IEnumerable<TItem> source, Func<TItem, bool> predicate)
    Parameters
    Type Name Description
    System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<TItem> source
    System.Func<TItem, System.Boolean> predicate

    A delegate to test each element for a condition.
    Returns
    Type Description
    TItem

    The last element in a sorted collection that satisfies the predicate delegate. If no such an element was found, a System.InvalidOperationException exception will be thrown.
    Type Parameters
    Name Description
    TItem
    Remarks

    The collection is expected to be sorted. Otherwise this method can yield unexpected results.
    While the standard System.Linq.Enumerable.Last``1(System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable{``0},System.Func{``0,System.Boolean}) iterates and caches the complete collection in order to produce a correct result for unsorted collections, LastInSorted<TItem>(IEnumerable<TItem>, Func<TItem, Boolean>) expects a sorted collection to avoid iterating the complete collection and therefore to significantly improve the performance in terms of speed and memory footprint.

    Exceptions
    Type Condition
    System.ArgumentNullException

    The predicate is null.
    System.InvalidOperationException

    The collection does not contain any element that satisfies the predicate delegate.
